I'll be almost as wordy as Greg.

Let's start with the good, and I apologize that I'm starting at the beginning.
Greg's easy enough to follow. One of the things I love about writing in first person is the internal narration can be just as revealing as action.
The bad from my POV is he's talking to himself even more than some of my characters. That old Show & Tell saw? On the other hand, he's an ordinary guy relating a slice of life.

Now to the sex scene. I thought you ran long on it, but lengthwise it's about the same as some of mine. You didn't break badly from previous characterization. It's sex. You're allowed some leeway to be different between segments of life or for development.
The bad here? Sentence length. Your show/tell balance isn't as good as it could be. Again, that's distinct from the action/narration balance.
Overall you've got a decent core. I don't know how much else you've written. Greg & Alex aren't exciting action heroes, but whatever beats you've got going aren't falling on their face.

One recommendation: Talk out your writing during editing. It can pay off in a lot of ways, but I feel it could help you polish that.

Get a few more sex scenes under your belt. They still give me pause, but they're so much fun and quick to write once you can get in your character's head. Allow them to be action and character development. The emotion will follow.

Quoted By:
>>28320167
>Greg's easy enough to follow. One of the things I love about writing in first person is the internal narration can be just as revealing as action.
I've tried writing in 3rd person in the past, it just doesn't work. Not having that internal thought process there and having someone from the outside try and explain everything always makes the writing seem incredibly juvenile. Being able to go through the feelings and general whys of a characters thoughts is always the strongest part of what makes writing great over other mediums personally.
>The bad from my POV is he's talking to himself even more than some of my characters.
I never took that to be a absolutely literal "He is thinking absolutely every single sentence out in his head", it was always meant to be a way to show the thought process, which while it largely does manifest itself as 'talking to yourself' in his head, is also in part just thoughts flashing by unstructured to any specific sentence structure.
>That old Show & Tell saw?
I was getting annoyed myself with how much telling and not showing the narrative had, it's like that is 'cause the story was meant to be "short", which while clearly I'm terrible at being short, having all the information play out as it happens instead of it being explained to us through Greg would have made the narrative /even longer/.
>I thought you ran long on it, but lengthwise it's about the same as some of mine.
>The bad here? Sentence length. Your show/tell balance isn't as good as it could be. Again, that's distinct from the action/narration balance.
Gonna be honest with you, I thought the sex scene went by too quickly. Not in terms of raw length but in content to length, which I have a really bad problem with thanks to school forcing this kind of low content high length writing, and making it shorter cuts too much actual information for my liking.
(1/2)

Anonymous Wed 12 Feb 2020 10:01:15 No.28329253 Report

Which with the less is explicitly stated, the more the interpretation drifts from what I intended to write. (The "The curtains are red because I bloody wanted the curtains to be red, no deeper meaning bullshit here." principle.)
>Talk out your writing during editing. It can pay off in a lot of ways, but I feel it could help you polish that.
I speak how I write and vice versa, and I've been known to be wordy in person to the point people ask me (why I don't need) to breath, so that seeping into the writing as a issue makes sense. Plus I speak fast, which also sometimes adds to the low content high length writing.
>Get a few more sex scenes under your belt. They still give me pause, but they're so much fun and quick to write once you can get in your character's head. Allow them to be action and character development. The emotion will follow.
While I personally don't particularly care for sex scenes for the purpose of having a sex scene (the fact that one didn't even have any penis-in-vagnia action should be telling of that), I do like writing intimate character interaction. If it doesn't really play into the narrative in any real way beyond having them have sex, I don't see much point, which is why I don't write many. (Plus being a kissless virgin doesn't help matters, but hey, means I don't get as caught up with making the actual sex realistic over the characterization because I have zero frame of reference.)

Thanks for liking and reading it, most of the issues with the narrative are things I know I have a problem with, namely content to length (as exemplified by this being two posts), which while this won't do much for this story, I'll try to work on for stories in the future.
